// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// PART 2 DJ Seo

- DJ Seo, co-founder, president, COO of Neuralink.
- studied electrical engineering during undergrad
started out his research in MEMS (Micro-Electro-Mechanical Systems) to build this
tiny structure for temperature sensing. Spent his majority of his college years
building millimeter wave circuits for next gen telecommunication systems, for
imaging.
- PhD program at UC Berkeley, at the Berkeley Wireless Research Center looking at
building "XG" the next generation telecom (like 3G, 4G, 5G)
- during grad school, pursue whatever project he wanted
  worked on "smart bandaid", there were hypotheses that when you apply external
  electric field to a wound, you can accelerate the closing of the wound, in
  collaboration with Pr Michel Maharbiz (known for remote control of beetles)

interested in understanding the purpose of things
building tech to understand the brain, not until graduate school
fascinated by building physical stuff
- key events that lead him to do what he's doing now:
  - growing up, both sides of his family, grandparents had very severe form of Alzheimer
  - when he was a teenager, came to the US, didn't speak a word of english, lot
  of struggle to connect with other people, so spent a lot of time alone, reading sci-fi books,
  especially the "Ender's Game" saga by Orson Scott Card (visual @ 1:31:50) &
  Neuromancer by William Gibson, and Snow crash by Neal Stephenson, and movies
  like the matrix, influenced him on the impact that tech can have on our lives
- brain is incredible fragile but also incredibly plastic & resilient

- 2013, holy grail of implantable systems is to understand how small of a thing
you can make (a lot of that is driven by how much energy/power you can supply
to it & how you extract data from it)
At that time at Berkely there was this desire to understand, in the neural space,
what kind of system you build to really miniaturize these implantable systems.
Michel: "I think I have a solution", the solution is ultrasound, then whe proceeded
to kind of walk through why that is the case, that formed the basis for his thesis
work called "neural dust".
- "neural dust": tiny, wireless sensors designed to be implanted in the body to
monitor and interact with nerves, muscles or organs. Powered & communicate using
ultrasound.

- said the word "kind" a lot (lol)

- the body is mostly salt water at 37 degrees Celsius, which is an extremely
harsh environment for any electronics to survive
- electromagnetic waves don't penetrate through this env well, and because of
the wave length the devices needs to be quite big
- general good rule of thumb is that you want the wavefront to be roughly on
the order of the size of the thing you're interfacing with.
so implant that is 10 to 100 micron -> would have to operate at hundreds of GigaHertz,
which is hard to build & the body attenuates that very significantly
- ultrasound travels a lot more effectively in the human body tissue compared
to electromagnetic waves, because ultrasound waves are compressive which is a
completly different mode of wavefront propagation
- ultrasound to power the device & getting data back
- how to get the data back? backscattering
- backscattering is a phenomenon in which particles or waves are scattered back
in the direction from which they came after interacting with a material.
  - used with RFID cards (Radio Frequency ID tag) (ex on credit cards), no battery
  inside, there's an antenna and some sort of coil with serial ID
  the reader sends a wavefront, it reflect back that wavefront with some sort
  of modulation that's unique to your ID.
  - we can use piezoelectric crystal to convert ultrasound to electricity & vice versa.
- history of BCI (brain computer interface)
  - 1790s: concept of animal electricity discovered by Luigi Galvani
    connected set of electrodes to frog leg
  - 1920s, Hans Berger discovered EEG & electroencephalography
  - 1940s, Renshaw, Forbes, Morrison inserted glass micro electrodes into the
  cortex and recorded single neurons.
  - 1950s, Hodgkin & Huxley build the model of biological neurons that describes
  the action potentials of a neuronal biological membrane
  - 1969, Eb Fetz (Univ of Washington) published paper "Operating Conditioning
  of Cortical Unit Activity", he was able to record a single unit neuron from a
  monkey & was able to have the monkey modulated based on its activity & reward system
  - 1980s paper by Apostolos Georgopoulos, discovered "motor directional tuning curve",
  single neurons in the motor cortex exhibit maximal activity for a particular
  "preferred" movement direction.
- he's interesting about taping into the high res, high fidelity of the signals

- brain is mad out of billions of neurons, interconnected in a network constantly
changing, bathed in this charged environment (potassium, sodium, clorine ions)
Neurons have a membrane with a protein structure called the voltage-gated selective ion channels
- when we put an electrode next to a neuron we're trying to captures these local
changes in the potential, mediated by the movements of the ions.
- 2 dominant physics domain: diffusion physics (farther from src)
& electromagnetism (close to src), which one dominates depends where the electrode is
when you are close, you get the typical spike, once you are further away (100 micron)
you no longer hear from that neuron (can't record that local change of the membrane)
- 100x100micron contains roughly 40 neurons
- you want to listen to the neurons & let the software do the job of decoding
- most neurons are usually very quiet

- how does neuralink work?
neural link implant in january in the first human (Noland)
  - 3 major components (image at 2:16:47 https://youtu.be/Kbk9BiPhm7o?si=aPd3-q23Z47Oo4k8&t=8207)
    - N1 implant or "the link": the device that records these neural chatters
    - R1, surgical robot that implants the tiny wires (threads)
    - B1 app: software to decode the signals, running very simple ML model that
    enable the first user Noland to move a cursor
  - done wirelessly
  - the implant is a two-part: "the link" has these flexible threads that have
  multiple electrodes along its length, they're only inserted into the cortical
  layer (3 to 5 mm in the human brain) in the motor cortex region
  64 of these threads, each with 16 electrodes along the span of 3 or 4 mm.
  Seperated by 200 microns
  & there's custom integrated circuit (ASIC) that amplifies the signals & digitizing it
  and has some mechanism for detecting if there were an interesting event detected,
  and then decide to send that through bluetooth to an external device (phone or
  computer) running the Neuralink app.
  Total of (64*16) 1024 electrodes, sampling at just under 20kH with 10 bit each = 200 Mb,
  needs compression & filtering to only send interesting data!
  width of thread starts from 16 micron to 84 micron
  at the end of thread there's a loop the robot can grab to implant it

  each electrode can record between 0 to 40 neurons but practically speaking
  we only see about 2 or 3 at most.

  BOSS algorithm: spike detection algorithm (Buffer online spike sorter)
  it outputs 6 unique values

  flexible electrodes

  There's an external charging device, charging is done through inductive charging but need to be careful not to be too hot
  most of the volume of implant is the (rechargable) battery
  about the size of quarter, 9mm thick
  the hole in the cranium get replaced by this implant

- still ongoing interrogation on the durability/longetivity & reliability of
these micro electrodes

- utah array, array of rigid needles (not flexibles) (1997) only one electrode
on each needle, no active electronics

- how do you build design something like this?
  - material selection (nothing really unique)

- patient registery: people can apply
  then there's a selection
  prescreening interview process
  then go to their homes to do a BCI home audit
- bunch of tests, FMRI, to locate where to put the electrodes
  they try to locate the "hand knob area" in the motor cortex
- surgery 2 to 4 hours
  - anesthesia induction
  - intra-op CT imaging to make sure we are drilling the hole in the right location
  - surgeon comes in, does their thing, skin incision, craniectomy, atherectomy
  - then robot inserts the threads (20 to 40 minutes)
  - surgeon closes this bitch up
- for Noland, one hour after the surgery, they made sure that they were recording
neural signals, and was already able to modulate a couple signals
- preparation: practice the surgery with pretty realistic models based on Noland
  (2:48:22)

- first goal/target of neuralink: telepathy: being able to communicate using
your mind wirelessly with a digital device
gotta train the brain to move a cursor

- some of the threads retracted resulting in a net decrease in the number of
effective electrodes, so they modified the recording algo to be more sensitive
which end up improving the initial results

