- DJ Seo, co-founder, president, COO of Neuralink.
- He first start explaining his background:
  - came to the US as a teenager, can't speak english, spent time alone reading
  sci-fi books
  - grandparents with severe form of Alzheimer
  - studied electrical engineering during undergrad
  - research in MEMS (Micro-Electro-Mechanical Systems)
  - PhD program at UC Berkeley
    - Wireless Telecommunication
    - "smart bandaid" in collaboration with Pr Michel Maharbiz
- Michel Maharbiz introduced the idea of ultrasound to build tiny implantable
systems that can be parked next to a neuron being able to record its state and
ping that back to the outside world
- That formed the basis for his thesis called "neural dust"
  - "neural dust": tiny, wireless sensors designed to be implanted in the body to
  monitor and interact with nerves, muscles or organs. Powered & communicate using
  ultrasound.
- explains why electromagnetic waves can't be used
  and why ultrasound works
- backscattering

- Explains the challenges to build tiny neuronal implants the size of neurons
and how ultrasound solved these challenges
- how neurons works and what the electrodes measures
- goes on about the science behind the electrodes



2:50:41

- power of the mind to visualize

- safety: the goal standard is to look at the tissue.
what trauma did you cause to the tissue
they have an entire department (of pathology) that looks at these tissue slices
  euthanize the animal (monkaX human be warned)
  go through necropsy to collect the brain tissue samples
  fix them in formalin
  gross them, section them
  then you look at individual slices
  this is used to evaluate the safety of the insertion mechanism as well as the threads
  FDA supervises this
  the standard for safety is really high, higher than a lot of operations

  they've been impressed by t he lack of immune response from the threads
  no damages detected
  R1 avoids vasculature

  how easy & safe to remove the implant?
  depends on when:
    - first 3 months after the surgery scar tissue is being made
    so it's quiete easy to pull them out, with minimal trauma
    - once the scar tissue forms, it gets harder, the current method:
    cutting the thread, then unscrewing & taking the implant out.
    They think it should be fine to leave the thread "forever"
    once the scar tissue is formed, the threads get anchored in place (don't move)

- they remove the dura to add the threads, but are looking for way to insert
them through the dura (but it's tough & opaque (can't see shit)), letting the
dura would decrease the scar tissue which would make it easier to remove threads
- upgrading
  - for nolan, cut the thread or remove them
  - at the moment: monolithic single implant
    could imagine 2-part implant: bottom the threads, top part for computational heavy loads with battery that you could remove

  Matthew MacDougall (head neurosurgeon at neuralink)

- key metrics to improve:
  - # of channels, current: 1024, end of year: 3k to 6k, next year: 16k
    limitation = photo lithographically print those wires, energy consumption, bandwidth, processing...
    It's always the interface that breaks, bonding this thin film array to the electronics
    how do you protect it, build an hermetic barrier
- how to test that?
  accelerated life tester is a brain in a ALT chamber, it's a vessel with salt water + bunch of stuff to replicate brain environment
  increasing temperature in ALT chamber speed up the aging process
  current version has been there for 2.5year => equivalent to 10 years

- neuralink is in a PCTFE box which has excellent chemical resistance...

- possible to have multiple neuralink implants?
  that's the goal, monkeys have had 2, one in each hemisphere

- blindside (or is it blindsight?), goal is to put implant in visual cortex &
do simulation (more than recording)
  they have been able of stimulating through our thin film array as well as
  other electronics for years (especially for re-activating limbs)
- our understanding of visual system is not very well developed, we know things
about the areas, and how certain zone detect certain shapes, but we don't know
where cognition arise, where color are encoded
- so to bring sight back, we would need an external camera, convert it into
a signal, simulated in the brain, to at least be able to detect edges of objects
- we could think of using more advanced camera to see UV and shit, to go beyond
what human are usually capable to do!

-would you implant a neuralink implant? absolutely, maybe not right now
10, 15, 100 BPS

- primary goals with early patients is to understand the safety of the device &
process. & understand efficacity & impact
early feasability study, learn to improve the device & surgery before embarking
into pivotal study: much larger trial, to look at statistical significance of
our endpoints, that is required before you can market the device

other applications
2 programs:
- movement: digital freedom to control cursor, then try to improve that to the
physical world, to move robotic arms...
speech (requires movement)
- vision

can we get insight into thoughts 

do you see a world with millions of people with neuralink implants?
I do, there are millions of people with neuronal damanges
there's a real possibility to see 8 billion people (everyone) with neuralink

