- full procedure of N1 implant
  - really simple, straightforward procedure (the human part of the surgery)
  one of the most basic,
  - making a cut in the skin on the top of the head where the representation of
  hand intentions is the most potent. (the hand knob)
  - flap the skin open
  - make a perfectly round 1 inch diameter hole in the skull
  - remove that bit of skull
  - open the lining of the brain
  - show that part of the brain to the robot, and let the robot do its stuff
  - then (human) puts the implant into that hole in the skull, screwing it down
  to the skull, sewing the skin back
  - few hours long, extremely low risk

- human vs robot
  - human are more generalized, and can modify the plan on the go

- lot of practice, everything is tested extremely rigorously
- practice on animals, hundreds of animal surgeries
- for first human, engineers built lifelike models, puslating brain, in a custom
3D printed skull that matches exactly the patient's anatomy (4:14:29)

- surgery on Noland
  - partners at the Barrow Neurologic Institute made everything as easy as possible for the trial
  help on how to arrange the details
  - much more high pressure surgery (not really about safety of the participant)
  but the number of observers, people watching live streams in the hospital
  (anxious about that, about possible unknown unknowns)
  - he was extremely nervous
  - everything went well
  - he placed the robot, he placed the targets on the robot (using a mouse)
    - 4:21:03 lasso tool to select a prime area of brain real estate and it will
    automatically avoid the blood vessels and automatically place a bunch of
    targets that allows the human robot operator to select really good areas of
    the brain

- with neurosurgery you can get anywhere in the brain (it's routine for him to
put deep brain stimulating electrodes near the very bottom of the brain, entering
from the top, using a robot from Globus)
  - take a preoperative MRI
  - put the patient to sleep
  - put their head in a frame
  - take a CT scan of their head
  - merge the MRI & the CT in software
  - you have a plan based on the MRI
  - you get a trajectory to follow
  - the robot arm can show you the trajectory that you intended from the pre-op
  MRI & establish a very rigid holder through which you can drill a small hole
  in the skill & pass a small rigid hollow wire deep into that area of the brain
  & then put your electrode
  - (that's standard technology)
  - it's accepted that there's 1 in 100 patients who have a bleed somewhere in
  the brain (that's not acceptable for Neuralink)
- neuralink is focues entirely on cortical targets, surface targets, because
there are no easy way to put 100s of wire in the brain without damages. You
have much better vision (you can actually see what's happening)

!!!- sewing electrodes into the spinal cord as a potential workaround for a spinal
cord injury that would allow brain-mounted implant to communicate with spine-
mounted implant, to trigger muscular responses.
!!!They have that working in very crude forms in animals
  (doing grasp, moving their legs)


- there's a lot of variability in people brains & skulls,
they had to "disqualify" people with skin or skull too thin or too thick

- hand knob (4:34:04)
- vision is a little deeper in the brain (than the "hand knob"), maybe 1 cm deeper
than hand insertions

- neuralink arose partly after Utah arrays would failed routinely because it
would trigger a bad immune response
Neuralink approach of using tiny flexible elctrodes avoid a lot of the bleeding,
of the immune response, electrode longevity & functionality & the health of the
tissue immediately surrounding the electrode is excellent
(goes on for years now in their animal models)

- the brain controls almost everything, you can control fertility, so there're
a lot of possible applications

- would you have a neuralink chip implanted in your brain? "Yeah"
!!! - value proposition for the average person:
  - new way to interact with digital, faster, more efficient
  - recording speech intentions
    - to remove keyboard
    - speaking (in your mind) to an AI agent, that would answer you in an earphone
      you could silently ask for information and getting it read to you in your ear without anyone knowing
  - feels like we are cavemen, we're barely touching the surface, and will be able
  to do crazy things
  - can we make people able to take care of themselves

- technology on the academic side is progressing at light speed
  - paper out of UC Davis: an accurate and rapidly calibrating speech neuroprosthesis
  BCI able to recognize 125k words (thinking the word, BCI recognizes it)

- he has an RFID chip in his hand with his business card, opens the front door
of his house

- mysticism about putting electronics in our body
  there's still this inviable barrier that the skull represents in people's mind

- how much does neuroplasticity come into play
  - plasticity decreases with age
  - there way to increase it using electrical stimulation (not totally proven out)

- life & death
  - death is inevitable

