// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// PART 4: BLISS CHAPMAN
// brain interface software lead at Neuralink

from 5:06:11 to 6:48:59

- motivation to work at Neuralink:
  - met 100s of people with spinal cord injuries, ALS, and want to help them
- people want (need) independance
  - this is an engineering problem
  with the right resources, right team, we can make a lot of progress

- he was part of the team that interviewed and selected P1 (noland)
  he was in the operating room, monitoring live signals coming out of the brain (see each electrode coming to life)
  he works we the users everyday to develop new UX paradigm's decoding strategies
  part of the team that figured out how to recover useful BCI to new world record levels when the signal quality degraded
- watching the robot was boring
- waited the next morning (after the surgery) to do body mapping,
  when noland was imagining moving his index they could see a spike
  and now they can use that info to move a cursor

- body mapping: way to map out the signals we have access
  - present a visual to the user and say "imagine doing this", the visual is 
  a 3D hand opening and closing, or index finger modulating up & down
  - record the brain activity

- UX is underrated for BCI development in general
  - behavior alignment to neural signal
  - need to find the best things to think about to get the best signals

- what we try to measure: individual neurons producing action potentials which last about 1ms
  sampled at 20kH (so 1 ms -> 20 samples)
- then we can process the signal into "just where do we detect a spike or where do we not"
  so it's converted to a binary signal 1: spike, 0: no spike
- everything we care about for decoding can be represented in the frequency characteristics of spike trains
- so it allows to do a lot of compression, which can be sent via bluetooth

- isolate where the spike comes from?
  - there's a whole academic field about this (to figure out from which neuron a spike comes from)
  - at the current scale the number of neurons per electrode is relatively small, so it's not really a problem

- go over methods they are using or exploring to detect spikes
  - exploring new technique: spike band power: may be able to detect spikes from neurons too far away from the electrode
    (but more expensive, more data)

- latency
  they want to build the best "mouse"
  esport could be dominated by paralysed players with implants
  - you have like 75 ms lead time on any action
  - you have a higher ceiling performance
  - so for games where reaction time is important, you're winning EZ
  "we are already faster than what you would do with muscles"
  - latency currently from brain spike to cursor movement is about 22 ms
  while brain neuron to hand is about 75 ms
  - he said that Noland said feels like he's moving the cursor before he actually
  intended to do it
- current bottlenecks
  - (kind of hilariously) bluetooth low energy protocol has some restriction on
  how fast you can communicate, standard frequency is about 7.5 ms
  which will become too slow
  - how fast screens refresh, 120Hz is not fast enough

- bro keep changing the questions, it's kind of annoying

- about the neuralink app
  - the goal is to help an individual navigate his computer independently
  so need to control mouse & keyboard
  - the job of the app is to translate this wireless stream of brain data coming
  off the implant into control of the computer
  do that by mapping brain activity to sort of the HID inputs to the actual hardware
  (HID (Human Interface Device) is the protocol for communicating, input device events)

- decoding: process of taking statistical patterns of brain data and turning it
into, for example, a mouse movement
  - training step: user imagine doing different actions
  uses a deep neural network

  - best template matching system
    - variety of behavioral challenges & debugging challenges (when woorking with someone who's paralyzed)
    because you can't see what they are doing
  - calibration, you need to make the best UX to make sure user is doing the
  right thing consistently to get the best signals & being able to recognize that
  signal later
  - there's also a ML challenge to find which signal is the best one
  (like when the user has the best behavior)

  => biggest challenge of UX is making sure the user is imagining the right
  behavior and not something slightly different (during calibration)
  -> correct, precise calibration is difficult & an unsolved problem
  -> don't really know about the true user intention
  -> but doesn't need to be solved to get something useful

  => in his view, the core challenge is the labelling problem: how do you
  understand at a very, very fine resolution what the user's attempting to do
  (not solved problem)
  (THIS IS THE FUNDAMENTAL CHALLENGE)
  given a window of time where the user is expressing some behavioral intent,
  what are they really trying to do at the granularity of every millisecond
  (that's a task design problem, a UX problem, ML problem, software problem)

!!! => I think the main idea here is that there's a real challenge to detect
the true intention of the user, and the goal of the UX is to accurately detect
it & convert it to an action (moving cursor, clicking, scrolling...) as fast as
possible. UX gives a lot of controls that the user can tune (speed, smoothness,
friction... of cursor)

- we observe a degradation through time
  can be mitigated by user adapting its strategy
  it can also be mitigated through a combination of software features (like how fast cursor is moving, smoothness, friction)
- recalibrate, there's a system to recalibrate
- when you have a good model calibrated, you can continue using that without
needing to recalibrate it

- UX, you want a control surface that still makes it easy & intuitive for the
user to understand the state of the system & how to achieve what they want
- UX END goal: UX fades into the background completely, that it's subconscious to the user
- UX gives ability to calibrate models on his own, so user can explore what
work best (finding what the best action to imagine give the best signal/easiest
to decode)

let go of trying to control the fingers/hand & control the actual cursor

- how to measure performance, bits per second
  - goal is let users being able to control computers as good as regular people
  or even better/faster
  - (5:57:18) web grid: grid of targets, we compute a score depending on how
  fast & accurate they can select & how small target is
    - different modes
      - left click on the screen
      - or just go over
      - or left + right click
      - ...
      - simplest mode: blue target show up on screen, you left click it
  - BPS is computed by taking the log of the number of targets on the screen
  TIMES (the number of correct selections MINUS incorrect) DIVIDED by time window
  (take the log because of information theory)
  (credit from Dr Krishna Shenoy, neuroscientist)
  (you can subtract 1 to model a keyboard (because one is the delete key))
  LINK TO FORMULA: <https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7970827/>
    - Noland is the best in the world at this task
      - previous human WR: 4.2 to 4.6 BPS
      - Noland: 8.5 BPS, then 9.51 BPS
    - his own record is like 17 BPS
  - how to improve?
    - Noland good perf is because of his extreme focus & energy, dedicated.
    he can play for like 4 hours (he's grinding GIGACHAD)
    - we don't really know yet, how to improve BPS

- they update the app quite frequently (sometimes 4/5 times a day)
  - noland plays "snake" which is super hard, to tell if a new update is doing
  better or worse

- research sessions: actively tring different things 
  noland can work for like 8h a day, that can be hundereds of different models
- independant use

- 271 pages of notes taken from the BCI sessions in march

- decoder generalization?
  - signals are going to be different between P1 & P2
  ex: channel #123 of P1 will send != signals than channel #123 of P2
  - but the UX should be similar, unless it's overfitted to Noland

- bottlenecks
  - finding good architecture for model to do the neuro mapping
  - software stability & reliability, bunch of bugs degrading perf

6:19:26

- as number of channels increases, logarithmic improvement in control quality
- increasing the number of channel should increase the reliability without
having to modify the decoder itself

- when you imagine stuff, the neurons might fire more or less, the frequency
content of the signal (in the motor cortex) is very correlated with the output
intention (the behavioral task the user is doing).
"rate coding" is the name of that phenomenon
You can imagine that rate coding is like the only way the brain could represent
information (hypothesis). There's evidence in bats for ex, that there's temporal
codes
- so brain may represent information by changing the frequency of a neuron
firing, so what matter is the delta between base line & when signal is modulated.
The base line is different from day to day

- why not just use an eyetracker?
he's confident it's better, because of the ergonomy of how it fits into he life
don't need to be in right position, don't need help to set it up

- building the decoder is really about building the dataset & compiling it into
the weights of the model
  - one of the biggest challenge in designing the optimal model for BCI is that
  offline metrics don't necessarily correspond to online metrics

end: 6:48:59

