// PART 5: Noland Arbaugh
// First human with a neuralink implant
// from: 6:49:00 to 8:37:34

- diving accident in 2016 that left him paralized with no feeling from the
shoulders down. Ran into a lake with a bunch of guys, dive in, something happened
(don't know what, maybe received a kick to the left side of his head), and 
that's it, he was paralyzed. [bro wtf, that's crazy, bro broke his neck by doing
the most random shit]
- tried his best to survive & get better. Got a good group of people around him
to support him
- stay positive (is he coping?), watches TV, movies, anime, read
immediate acceptance
faith in god (it was all meant to happened, made his faith stronger)
stress-free guy
extrovert
- wants to try everything possible to make his life better

- should I do this? I could wait until number 2 or 3
but being the first one is pretty cool

- 7:05:51 footage of operation

- trust the people at Neuralink & Barrow with his life
they're the most impressive people in the world

- day of surgery:
  the night before, the morning, he was just excited, "let's make this happen"
  facetiming Elon (something went wrong with his plane)
  wasn't scared

  - at the hospital at 5:30 am
  went through all the pre-op stuff
  prayed
  surgery at 7AM
  woke up, played a bit of a prank on his mom, "who are you?"

- didn't feel any pain, didn't take any pain killer
- after surgery, some neuralink employee brought an ipad, they had put up 8
different channels that were recording some of his neuron spikes
So he started trying to wiggle his fingers, and a yellow spike appeared
(7:12:12)
everyone freaking out, started clapping
he's imagining moving his fingers, it's pretty easy for him to do

- after his accident they told him to keep trying to move his body because
that's going to (could) create new neural pathways or pathways in his spinal
cord to reconnect things to hopefully regain some movement
  - he imagine walking: it's imagining what he had to do to take a step
  which is hard, mentally & physically
  - like the kill bill movie, stare at body parts & say "move", "move your big
  toe"
  - it feels like there's a build up, it feels like there are signals that get
  stuck somewhere, and build up until they burst
  once they burst, he has a really weird sensation of everything dissipating.
  It's like a fatigue, like a muscle fatigue

- for the first few years all he was doing was looking at walls

7:19:05

- what they had him do, especially at the beginning is body mapping.
there's a visualization of a hand or an arm on the screen & he has to do that
motion. That's how they train the algo to understand what he's trying to do
  - he was already doing that, to hopefully get back some of his movements
  but neuralinkg actually gives him some feedback, he can see the signals in
  real-time
  - body mapping is essentially like body training

- was able to move the cursor within the first or second week
didn't seem like big of a deal to him, he expected that to happen

- difference between attempted movement & imagined movement
  - attempted movement: him physically trying to move
  (what he mostly did during the first weeks)
  - imagined movement: think about doing it, not attempting to do it at all,
  visualizing
  - is that supposed to be a different part of the brain that lights up?
  [Bliss Chapman in the background]: not necessarily
  (struggled to do this)
  - feels very different, imagined = mind control, attempted = movement
- realized he could directly move the cursor, just by thinking about moving it,
without attempting to move
- start seeing the spikes before he was actually attempting to move
one day, while playing webgrid, he was just moving his eyes to see the next
target and the cursor started moving toward this direction
=> so one day, he realized he could just imagine, not attempting to move, it
blew its mind, first time he was controlling with his mind (wasn't really
impressed before that)

- about the neuralink app: (visual at 7:36:55)
  - app to help him interact with the computer
  - there are few different settings
  - calibration: how to get cursor control
  5 min to calibrate
  the more time, the better the model gets
  - webgrid into it
  - this is how he connects to the computer in general

  - voice controls to connect to it
  - the charger is also how he connects to the app
  he has to have the implant charger over his head to be able to connect
  cause the implant is in hibernation mode
  - homework tab (todo list)
- him playing snake.io at 7:37:55
  if he can play snake decently well, then it means he has a pretty good model
- he's doing data collection daily
 (he's been slacking on)

- calibration is a bubble game (7:40:10)
  yellow bubble that pop up on the screen
  - at first it's open loop: no control over the cursor, cursor will be moving on its own across the screen
  and he's following it by intention
  - calibration with attempted movement works better than imagined movement
  and it generalizes to imagined movement
  - close loop: when he gets cursor control
  - 7 minutes for calibration
  for good models: 40 or 45 minutes

- webgrid
  - in march 89k targets
  - webgrid is grid that you can make a small or big as you want
  - a cell lights up & you ahve to click it
  - it's a way to benchmark BCI
  - the bigger the grid the more BPS
  - he's doing that on 35x35
  - !!!! vid of him playing at 8:15:50

  - BPS increases if you have multiple type of clicks
  (right (orange), left (blue))

  - right now, he's not clicking with his mind, he uses the dwell cursor, which
  has some latency

- before the threads retracted they were calibrating clicks
  85% of the implant's threads had retracted from his brain's motor cortex after a month
  big oof, he didn't want to lose any capability, he was ready to do another
  surgery, he was very sad
  - couple weeks to go back to previous performance
  they changed the way they measured the behavior of individual neurons
  switched from individual spike detection to spike-band power
  and now it got better

- excited to see the next users, to see what work for them, see if they have
new better ideas
  - hope they work hard, it's not just for us, but everyone that comes after us
  - don't be afraid to go to neuralink or ask him

- people like him just want independance
so neuralink helps do more things without his family around
